hey.

this is my attempt at filling out the behaviour of bash in an organised manner
we will go in chronological order

bash divides all words into, roughly, name, operator, and meta nodes
meta nodes influence how commands are queued up for execution
most other things fall into name nodes
	anything in quotes is, or is a part of, a name node
	wildcards '*' are an operator node (they lose meaning when put in quotes), but they otherwise follow syntax checking rules when regarded as part of a name node
	redirection operators '<>' consume the node on their right. if it is not a name node, that stops the input from running anything (syntax error)
meta nodes '&|()' require that:
	& and | need a command on both sides
	( and ) need a command on the inside of the bracket, and optionally a meta node on the outside (this isnt another bracket

fulfilling all that, bash will then move on to evaluate each command separately (will generally no longer stop the input from running because of errors)
using redirections with a glob (i.e. '> *.c') will emit 'ambiguous redirect' as an error and move on
general errors (invalid args, open error, read error, heredoc error, command not found, etc) will emit their own errors

and yeah thats it!






